2019-12-22 05:37:54	veek	what's an 'implicit global free variable' and why does he say 'An implicit global is a free variable for which the compiler has found no binding in an enclosing function scope.' I thought global vars were at the module level.. https://leanpub.com/insidethepythonvirtualmachine/read#leanpub-auto-the-view-from-30000ft
2019-12-22 05:38:14	-->	Poffer (~Poffer@200116b868347f000816b9dbc861a90d.dip.versatel-1u1.de) has joined #python
2019-12-22 05:38:18	<--	dnlserrano (~dnlserran@bl11-143-200.dsl.telepac.pt) has quit (Ping timeout: 265 seconds)
2019-12-22 05:39:10	-->	vorped (~vorped@ool-457308d3.dyn.optonline.net) has joined #python
2019-12-22 05:40:51	[Tritium]	"Global" means module scope.  What that means is python will look for a variable in module scope if it cant find it in local (function) scope
2019-12-22 05:41:43	[Tritium]	it only gets complicated if you assign to the name
2019-12-22 05:42:26	bjs	veek: so if you say `global foo` then the compiler knows that in that block (function body) the name "foo" refers to the global variable foo.
2019-12-22 05:42:56	bjs	veek: if you don't say that,  the compiler has to "look for" another variable called 'foo' in the enclosing scopes. e.g. if you have nested functions it has to go up until it finds one called "foo"
2019-12-22 05:43:28	-->	gunnaaaR (~gunnaaaR@s178255151130.blix.com) has joined #python
2019-12-22 05:43:29	bjs	veek: that line says, if you do all that and never find a variable called "foo" then you must be reading the module-level "global" foo
2019-12-22 05:43:48	-->	tedchange (tedchange@is.a.1337.fucker.bnc4you.xyz) has joined #python
2019-12-22 05:45:10	veek	bjs thanks
